In 1899 Mr. Thomson had also undertaken another book for

This was a plan the author had adopted, with good effect, not only in a special edition of Cranford (1898), but for some of his original drawings which came into the market after exhibition. Nothing can be more seductive than 3 Hugh Thomson pen-sketch, when delicately tinted in sky-blue, rose-Du Barry, and apple—green (the vert-pomme dear--as Gautier says—to the soft moderns)—a treatment which lends them a subdued but indefinable distinction, as of old china with a pedigree, and fully justifies the amiable enthusiasm of the phrase-maker who described their inventor as the “ Charles Lamb of illustration.''
